      <p>As you can see, the 50-second time gap in the system times should now fall within the valid times, to be able to simulate the example with the lost ID — at least for the span of 50 seconds. </p>
      <p>The correct setup is left as an exercise for the interested reader.</p>
      <p>Two queries that illustrate the values in the table are, for example, the following:</p>
      <fig>
         <desc>In this query, all documents are searched whose valid time range covers the period between 14:17 and 14:18. These are the split document and the original document. Both have the status "stolen", since the discovery was not reported until 14:18.</desc>
         <image href="../images/result1-x_64.png"/>
      </fig>
      <fig>
         <desc>If you change the time range to after 18:00, the original is — as expected — superseded by the update.</desc>
         <image href="../images/result2-x_65.png"/>
      </fig>
      <fig>
         <desc>The current version of the temporally managed document is stored in the "latest" collection.</desc>
         <image href="../images/result_3-x_66.png"/>
      </fig>
      <p>As you can see, with sufficient creative problem-solving, you can accomplish quite a lot with these queries. Also helpful is certainly the extensive list of comparison operators that MarkLogic provides for comparing time ranges: ISO Operators <xref format="html" scope="external"
               href="https://docs.marklogic.com/guide/temporal/searching#id_92200">ISO normierte Operatoren in MarkLogic zum Vergleichen von Zeiträumen</xref> and ALLEN Operators <xref format="html" scope="external"
               href="https://docs.marklogic.com/guide/temporal/searching#id_98704">Allen (ALN) Vergleichsoperatoren für Zeiträume</xref>.</p>
